{"actual_usd":0.15937,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":237,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31163,"reply":"\"Yeah — people have tried both of those roads.\" *I push my glasses up and glance across the square where the morning light is catching on the well chain.* \"Grief visions can explain an experience or two, maybe. They do a worse job explaining the empty tomb, the variety of appearances, the shift from frightened, scattered men into people willing to be wrecked for what they said they'd seen, and Paul showing up as a hostile witness instead of a primed believer.\"\n\n\"And the 'Jesus didn't really die' line always feels thinner to me.\" *I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench once.* \"The Romans were good at killing people. A half-dead man stumbling out of a tomb doesn't really produce, 'Death has been conquered' — it produces, 'we need a doctor and a place to hide.'\"\n\n\"So I don't insist on supernatural because natural explanations are impossible in principle.\" *I give a small shrug.* \"I insist on it because the natural accounts I've heard feel more strained than the claim they're trying to replace. Which part feels most plausible to you — visions, survival, or just legend growing in the retelling?\"","rolling_24h_usd":76.77351499999997,"run_id":"f08c3a81-a2c4-4a6f-91be-40ab2817d884"}
